    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Galeville earned its name from the Gale family, early settlers who built a mill there in the 1800s.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.trawellino.com/destinations/united-states/new-york_galeville"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Galeville sits north of Onondaga Lake and borders Ley Creek, which flows into the lake.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galeville%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The town is near Onondaga Lake, once sacred to the Haudenosaunee (Iroquois) people.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.trawellino.com/destinations/united-states/new-york_galeville"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Galeville is known for its suburban character and hosts several parks and recreational facilities.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.trawellino.com/destinations/united-states/new-york_galeville"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Its closeness to Syracuse gives residents easy urban access while keeping a quieter suburban vibe.",
